  "prompt": "What are some common myths that are not true?",
  "response": "Certainly! There are many myths that people commonly believe to be true, but are actually false. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. **Napoleon was very short**: Contrary to popular belief, Napoleon Bonaparte was not unusually short. In fact, he was around average height for his time, about 5'6\" or 5'7\". The myth likely arose due to a misunderstanding of French measurements or propaganda.\n\n2. **You only use 10% of your brain**: This myth suggests that humans only use a tiny fraction of their brain. In reality, we use most parts of our brain almost all the time, even when we are sleeping. Different tasks and functions activate various areas of our brain.\n\n3. **Goldfish have a 3-second memory**: Goldfish actually have a much longer memory span than 3 seconds. Studies have shown they can remember things for months.\n\n4. **Bats are blind**: Bats are not blind. Most bats have quite good eyesight, and they rely on echolocation as a primary sense to navigate and find food in the dark.\n\n5. **Cracking your knuckles causes arthritis**: There is no scientific evidence to support that cracking your knuckles leads to arthritis. The sound is caused by the release of gas bubbles in the synovial fluid in the joint.\n\n6. **Mount Everest is the closest point to space**: While Mount Everest is the tallest mountain from sea level, the point closest to space is actually Mount Chimborazo in Ecuador, due to the Earth's equatorial bulge.\n\n7. **Sugar causes hyperactivity in children**: Despite popular belief, studies have not found a strong link between sugar consumption and hyperactive behavior in children.\n\n8. **Vikings wore horned helmets**: There is no historical evidence to suggest that Vikings wore helmets with horns. This image was popularized by operatic depictions and other artwork centuries after the Viking era.\n\n9. **Putting a tooth in milk after it falls out will ensure it can be reattached**: While placing a tooth in milk can help preserve it, immediate replantation or contact with a dentist is crucial. Prompt action is more important than the method of preservation.\n\n10. **Humans have five senses**: It's more accurate to say humans have many senses, including balance (equilibrioception), temperature (thermoception), pain (nociception), and body position (proprioception), among others.\n\nThese are just a few examples of myths that have been debunked. It\u2019s always good to question and research widely-held beliefs to uncover the truth!",
